41 square feet of commercial space.
42 (f) Unless a unit adopts an ordinance to opt out of this section,
2026 IN 1001—LS 7120/DI 87

26
1 a unit may not establish any minimum parking space requirements
2 for the following:
3 (1) A dwelling that is not more than one thousand two
4 hundred (1,200) square feet.
5 (2) A commercial space that is less than three thousand
6 (3,000) square feet.
7 (3) Affordable housing.
8 (4) A senior housing property.
9 (5) A child care center licensed under IC 12-17.2-4.
10 (6) A ground level nonresidential space in a mixed use
11 building.
12 (7) A building, including a vacant building, undergoing a
13 change of use:
14 (A) from a nonresidential to a residential use; or
15 (B) for a commercial use.
16 (g) Unless a unit adopts an ordinance to opt out of this section,
17 a unit may not adopt or enforce any ordinance, rule, or regulation
18 that limits the maximum number of parking spaces for any
19 residential type, including single family dwellings, duplexes,
20 triplexes, fourplexes, townhouses, accessory dwelling units,
21 multi-family residential dwellings, or any commercial or mixed use
22 development.
23 (h) A unit may request a variance from the requirements of this
24 section by submitting a request to the fire prevention and building
25 safety commission, if the unit can show that compliance with this
26 section would be hazardous to the life, health, and safety of
27 residents. A unit's variance request must be supported with the
28 written opinion of a building official or fire chief.
29 (i) A unit may request a variance to require additional parking
30 spaces permanently marked for the exclusive use of individuals
31 with disabilities in a number that exceeds the minimum required
32 for compliance with the Americans with Disabilities Act (42 U.S.C.
33 12101 et seq.) based upon on the planned or likely population,
34 location, or safety of a building, using objective standards.
35 Sec. 19. (a) This section applies to structure classified as an R-2
36 building occupancy classification under the Indiana building code
37 adopted by the fire prevention and building safety commission.
38 (b) A residential building with not more than four (4) floors
39 above grade shall be permitted to have only one (1) stairway if:
40 (1) the building is equipped with a sprinkler system compliant
41 with the state fire code; and
42 (2) the stairway:
2026 IN 1001—LS 7120/DI 87

27
1 (A) complies with state fire code requirements, including
2 fire-rated doors at each floor; and
3 (B) is constructed of fireproof material.
4 (c) A residential building with five (5) or six (6) floors above
5 grade may have only one (1) stairway if:
6 (1) the building area is not more than four thousand (4,000)
7 square feet per floor;
8 (2) the maximum exit access travel distance shall not exceed
9 one hundred twenty-five (125) feet;
10 (3) the building is equipped with a sprinkler system compliant
11 with the state fire code;
12 (4) a manual fire alarm system and automatic smoke detection
13 system that activates the occupant notification system in
14 accordance with the state building and fire code is provided,
15 with smoke detectors located in common spaces outside of
16 dwelling units, including but not limited to gathering areas,
17 laundry rooms, mechanical equipment rooms, storage rooms,
18 interior corridors, interior stairways, and exit passageways;
19 (5) openings to the interior exit stairway enclosure are limited
20 to openings:
21 (A) required for exit access into the enclosure from
22 normally occupied spaces;
23 (B) required for egress from the enclosure; and
24 (C) to the exterior;
25 (6) elevators do not open into the interior exit stairway
26 enclosure;
27 (7) electrical receptacles are not installed in an interior exit
28 stairway; and
29 (8) the stairway:
30 (A) complies with state fire code requirements, including
31 fire-rated doors at each floor; and
32 (B) is constructed of fireproof material.
33 Sec. 20. This section applies to structure classified as an R-2
34 building occupancy classification under the Indiana building code
35 adopted by the fire prevention and building safety commission. A
36 unit may not require a structure that is not more than:
37 (1) six (6) stories; and
38 (2) twenty-four (24) total units;
39 to have a passenger elevator larger than an elevator that
40 accommodates a wheelchair.
41 Sec. 21. Nothing in this chapter:
42 (1) affects a unit's regulation of short term rentals as under
2026 IN 1001—LS 7120/DI 87

28
1 IC 36-1-24;
2 (2) prohibits property owners from enforcing rules or deed
3 restrictions imposed by a homeowners association or by other
4 private agreement;
5 (3) supersedes applicable building codes, fire codes, or public
6 health and safety laws;
7 (4) relieves a person from obtaining a required permit;
8 (5) prohibits a unit from taking enforcement actions, imposing
9 fines, penalties, or requiring project modifications to bring a
10 development into compliance; or
11 (6) affects a restrictive covenant or regulation of a
12 condominium association or homeowners' association.
13 Sec. 22. A zoning ordinance adopted before July 1, 2026, is void
14 to the extent the ordinance conflicts with this chapter. However,
15 this chapter does not apply to or affect any application for a permit
16 under IC 36-7-4 submitted to a unit before July 1, 2026.
17 Sec. 23. A person adversely affected or aggrieved by a violation
18 of this section may bring an action against the unit for:
19 (1) declaratory and injunctive relief; and
20 (2) costs and reasonable attorney's fees.
21 SECTION 18. An emergency is declared for this act.
